                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="17645" author="joerg.heinicke@gmx.de" created="Mon, 15 May 2006 22:30:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;TestCase for scoped beans. The text will be successful with proxyTargetClass=&quot;true&quot;, but it will fail for proxyTargetClass=&quot;false&quot; with ClassCastException.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18069" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 19 Jun 2006 08:24:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Have you had a chance to test your scenario against the reworked scoping support in 2.0 M5 (or in a 2.0 RC1 snapshot) yet? We have significantly reworked the entire facility, so you might want to check this against the 2.0 RC1 release (due tomorrow) if you haven&apos;t already used M5.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18073" author="joerg.heinicke@gmx.de" created="Mon, 19 Jun 2006 08:41:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No, I were on vacation last nearly two weeks and have not been trying out 2.0 M5 yet. I will wait for RC 1 then.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18169" author="joerg.heinicke@gmx.de" created="Fri, 23 Jun 2006 01:36:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So, in the meantime I could run the test with 2.0 RC 1 and it works (using ScopedProxyFactoryBean). There is only an issue with the detection whether to use CGLib or JDK dynamic proxy. I get a CGLib proxy though I implement an interface and though enforcing a JDK dynamic proxy (during remote debugging) works too. So this issue itself (JDK dynamic proxies don&apos;t implement the interfaces of the to-be-proxied objects) seems to be fixed while the detection when to use CGLib and when to use JDK dynamic proxy does not - and the property &quot;proxyTargetClass&quot; is ignored. Do you want a new Jira issue entry for this?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18304" author="robh" created="Wed, 28 Jun 2006 23:54:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;J&#246;rg, &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Scoped proxies are intended to be class proxies by default to prevent any strange errors when using them through the transparent &amp;lt;aop:scoped-proxy/&amp;gt; mechanism. However, the value of proxyTargetClass=false should now trigger the explicit creation of a JDK proxy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rob&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
